1.title: Trying New Things
1.plot: It's post-college graduation and newly reunited high school friends Nut, Jeanie and Connor gather together to cross some things off the bucket list.

2.title: The Morning After
2.plot: Jeanie, Connor and Nut recover from the shenanigans of the night before and Rita gives Jeanie some motherly advice about life post-grad.

3.title: SAT Prep
3.plot: Connor hijacks a high school SAT prep class as a means to make an extra buck.

4.title: Dick Pic
4.plot: Connor and Nut attempt to photograph the ultimate dick pic and Jeanie disapprovingly argues its merits, (or lack there of).

5.title: Fourth of July
5.plot: Jeanie tries to network at the Tompkins' annual Fourth of July mixer, while Nut and Connor face off with rival Todd Dick and his crew of lackeys.

6.title: Country Time
6.plot: Before Jeanie can leave for her big job interview, Connor calls an important pitch meeting for his revolutionary new business.

7.title: Bad Date
7.plot: Jeanie goes on a date with Todd Dick, Connor realizes his true feelings for Jeanie, and Nut and Connor sabotage Jeanie's date.

8.title: B* of Honor
8.plot: Jeanie delivers a drunken speech at her younger sister's bridal dinner, while Connor promotes his business venture.

imdb.plot outline: Three friends from high school, unable to secure employment or a decent income post college graduation, are forced to move back home to live with their parents. Jeanie McNulty, a type-A overachiever and formerly obese high school nerd, returns home to live with her thrice-divorced gold-digging mother and her soon-to-be-wed perfect younger sister. Connor O'Connor, a communications major with wild dreams of get-rich-quick success, finds himself at home with, Rita, his loving albeit enabling single mom. Nathaniel Ulysses Tompkins, affectionately known as Nut, works as an office assistant in his father's successful law firm, yet longs to pursue the life of a starving artist. Together, the three 'losers' attempt to become normal adults complete with jobs, financial security, and family; while at the same time struggling to leave behind dorm room life, weekend parties, and living under their parents' health insurance.
